title: For Sale:  Antique Gambling Kit with Colt 1849 pocket pistol
postcontent: This is an antique Gambling travel kit with hidden Colt 1849 pocket pistol and accessories. The box appears to be made from either rosewood or mahogany and is approx 12 inches wide and seven inches tall by 8.5 inches deep. It has 3 layers including a hidden layer and a hidden drawer. The top layer of the box contains antique clay poker chips, antique bone hand made dice. Vintage poker dice in leather case, an antique pocket watch case made into a hand held dice game. An antique wooden treen roulette wheel that spins. An antique complete set of cards in a box labeled "Pelham Playing Cards Boots Cash Stationers" The cards were made by Goodall & Sons London. It also has two matching antique glass containers and two wooden turned dice cups in different sizes. It also has what appears to be a very old paper with antique cards on it. If you lift up the brass loops on the side of the box, it has a hidden Colt 1849 pocket pistol, a wooden screwdriver, an antique powder flask (with a few dents), an antique colt patent bullet mold, and a glass jar without lid (where you would expect to see a percussion cap tin). The Colt pistol is in good to very good condition and appears to function properly. Please see pics for condition. If you press the button in the middle back of the kit, it releases a spring drawer out the front of the box. This drawer contains a pair of antique eyeglasses in a leather case, and antique straight razor made in Germany, a pocket knife made by IXL George Wostenholm, 2 antique wizard sleeve card cheating tools pat date 1888, an antique tin photo of two guys playing poker and another set of poker dice. This is really a very cool and unique set.

I am going to do something that will surprise folks on backpage...I am going to post an AR15 for trade, that is NOT "made of platinum" or of "unobtainium", and no...I don't even think it's worth "One MILLION Dollars".

 It is a new, unfired, Anderson Arms 16" M4 pattern carbine.

 It has MagPul furniture, and a MagPul MBUIS rear flip-up sight. Five x 30-round PMags, and 500 rounds of Tula (non-corrosive) ammo in a spam can.

 I own this rifle/PMags/ammo combo for $659 (rifle) $75 (PMags) $119 (ammo). That is a total of $853 + about $85 in sales tax.

I am not going to lose money on the rifle, but I don't need it (I have more AR's than I really know what to do with), so I want to make a FAIR trade to both parties. I am NOT looking for one of those "TRADE IN MY FAVOR" kind of deals that twatwaffles on backpage seem to be looking for so they can screw another guy, and I am not under any illusion that this rifle is "special" in any way, or rare, or a collector's dream, or masturbatory fuel for some tacticool dude with delusions of Low Speed High Drag Operashuns while making a tactical exfiltration from his favorite donut shop with his 400lbs of fat stuffed into his knockoff tacticool clothes as he regales people with stories of when he was "with the teams" or other such nonsense.

 I want to make a FAIR deal to ME, and to YOU. This is a basic, working, decent quality AR carbine with a LOT of bang for your buck when you figure in the ammo and mags.

 These are some of the things I am looking for:

 1. Glock 35, Gen 3 with a decent number of magazines and a bit of cash ($200).

 2. 5" 1911 from Springfield Armory (Range Officer or LOADED Model)- Straight Across.

 3. Smith & Wesson Model 25 in 4" or 5" - Straight Across


 I am not really interested in other trades or models. I especially do NOT want any shotguns, or SKS, or anything of that nature.

 Let's be realistic, and FAIR to each other. Let's make a deal we are BOTH happy with, and not trying to get over on one another. Yes....maybe my rifle CAN be bought somewhere for XYZ dollars...I don't care. I listed what I honestly PAID for it, and the ammo, and the PMags. I am NOT trying to put anyone together, or come out on top.

 Have a great day, and a great New Year.

 By the way...I am in the San Tan Valley area around Hunt Hwy and Bella Vista. I'd like to trade with an East Valley guy or gal.

 We can meet at Dunkin Donuts at Hunt Hwy near Gary Road, and I can buy you a coffee when we make the trade, and NO I don't weigh 400lbs and wear knockoff tacticool clothes! 

P.S. I will sell the rifle and ALL the PMags and Ammo for $800 FIRM.

title: For Sale:  Klingenthal French Sword-Model 1845-Infantry
postcontent:
Script on top blunt edge of sword says "Manuf re Klingenthal Coulaux & Cie"
No scabbard.

Manufre de Klingenthal Coulaux & Cie markings indicated the disastrous Franco-Prussian war of 1870. The French moved the government manufacturing of swords to Châtellerault.
On September 1870, Klingenthal was captured by the Germans. Alsace remained a German territory until 1918. The company produced some bayonets for the German Empire (bearing the mark C ) but was never able to challenge the manufacturers of Solingen (Germany). The making of tools and the few orders for blades for private swordmakers were not sufficient to stop the decline of the Manufacture de Klingenthal. 

In 1815, six hundred workers were making swords in Klingenthal, in 1910 they were one hundred. In 1955 only fifteen men were employed in the tool manufacturing company of Klingenthal, which closed its doors permanently in 1962.
